author: Cape Cod Times sports@capecodonline.com
title: High schools: D-Y's Conley accounts for all the scoring in 6-0 field hockey win over Nauset
text: Posted Oct. 9, 2015 at 11:04 PM By Cape Cod Times Posted Oct. 9, 2015 at 11:04 PM » Social News SOUTH YARMOUTH - Taylor Conley had a hand in all six goals as the Dennis-Yarmouth Dolphins blanked the Nauset Warriors in Atlantic Coast League field hockey action on Friday afternoon. Hannah Morse helped Dennis-Yarmouth (5-3, 3-1 ACL) to a slim 1-0 lead at the half. Conley, a senior captain, then got to work, netting all four of her goals in the second half while assisting Anna McGaffigan on a goal en route to the 6-0 final. McGaffigan and Summer Walsh added an assist each in the win Lucy McNamara kept Nauset (4-6, 0-4 ACL) in the game with 26 saves. Falmouth 3, Marshfield 0: MaryAlyce Bevaqua scored two goals and the Clippers shutout the Rams in Falmouth. Ericka Meissner opened the scoring from younger sister, Alexia, as Falmouth scored all three goals in the first half. Hannah Callahan assisted on Bevaqua’s first goal while Quinn O’Rourke setting up the second. Brittany Welch, Chloe Crago and Rachel Curtis excelled defensively for the Clippers (5-1-2), who kept pace with D-Y at 3-1 in the ACL. Falmouth hosts the Dolphins this morning at 11 a.m. Apponequet 2, Bourne 1: A pair of late goals by the Lakers spoiled a strong performance by the Canalmen in Lakeville. Annie Cheney staked Bourne (6-4-1) to a 1-0 lead with six minutes left in the opening half off an assist from Carly LaCasse. Jenna Sundquist recorded eight saves in net for the Canalmen while Audrey Kelleher excelled defensively. VOLLEYBALL Sandwich 3, Sturgis East 1: The Blue Knights bounced back from an opening game loss to take the next three games and win the match over the Storm at the Hyannis Youth & Community Center. Sturgis East (9-2) battled throughout, taking the first game 26-24. The Storm lost their middle mitter Arianna Jackson to a left ankle injury in the second game, a 25-10 victory for Sandwich (9-2), with the Blue Knights taking the following two games 25-17, 27-25 for the win. Junior Caroline Clabault led Sandwich with 25 kills and six blocks while junior Kaylee Tolman had nine aces at the service line. Senior Liz Siranosian led the Sandwich defense with 25 digs and Tolman added 15. Senior Abigail Bates spread the offense for the Blue Knights with 27 assists. Lauren Smith and Amanda Sullivan spread the Sturgis East offense with 13 and 16 digs respectively while also proving strong on defense with 11 and 15 digs respectively. Delaney Wood was also key for the Storm on defense, with 27 digs. Hannah Conklin sparked the Sturgis East offense with 16 kills while Deja Andrews added 14. Jill Doyle filled in well for Jackson at middle hitter, finishing with three blocks on the match. Nauset 3, Cape Tech 0: The Warriors used strong defense and communication in beat the Crusaders 25-17, 25-16, 25-14 n Harwich. Lexi Napolitano led the way for Nauset (4-7) with 12 kills and two aces while Sara Trauterman (four aces) and Isabel Hansen (one ace) sparked the offense with six kills each. Taylor Hughes spread the offense around with 12 assists while adding a pair of aces and four digs defensively. Mattison Clements added seven digs while Necol Sosa had four digs and seven aces. Whitney Enobakhare added a pair of aces while Alyssa Birchfield added four aces and two kills. Bourne 3, Wareham 0: Miranda Partosan knocked down eight kills while Aly Hickey used 18 assists to help the Canalmen beat the Vikings 25-19, 25-14, 25-15 in Wareham. Partosan added eight digs to her day for Bourne (9-3) while Hickey also had 12 digs and four aces. Freshman Kameryn McAnaugh added 13 points at the service line and four kills while Leah Hidenfelter had 13 digs, four aces and 12 points. The Canalmen used improved communication and improved serving the hand the Vikings the loss. Coyle-Cassidy 3, St. John Paul II 1: The Lions were strong at the service line against the Cardinals but fell in Taunton 15-25, 16-25, 25-14, 23-25. Junior Jess Tierney led St. John Paul II (7-7) with six aces at the line, 12 assists and three digs defensively. Junior Kaia Whiteley added 13 kills, a pair of aces, five digs and eight blocks to the Lions’ cause while junior Casey Sullivan added five digs and one kill. By Cape Cod Times
